	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have read your posts about grouping and I would like to add my 2 cp's worth.<br><br>First of all, when fighting in groups, I always have at least one or two high level spells memorized, at least one spell of a lower level, root, and Tishan's Clash.<br><br>When starting a fight with a creature yellow or red, I wait until the tanks take off anywhere from 15- 20% of the monsters health and cast my most powerful spell on it, then immediately sit down and med. During this time I watch the health of the monster, plus the health of my group members. When the monster loses about another 20- 25% of his health I cast another spell, which one really depends on how many tanks are in the group. sometimes I cast another powerful one, sometimes I cast a weaker one. In a situation where we have at least 2 tanks and a healer, i try not to cast more than twice per fight against yellows or reds. Sometimes I may need to cast more if the tanks are taking too much damage (especially if we have no healer). I never pull mobs on me using this method, and I am usually alway the only one who always has full health (this has caused a couple of people to get mad at me who didnt understand the role of the caster).<br><br>When fighting blacks (whites), or blues, or greens, I try not to use my more powerful spells, and cast a weaker one, or maybe Tishan's Clash to stun them for a little while. I usually cast at least once with a black, but hardly ever against a blue or green...unless our tanks are taking too many hits. During these fights I am always medding.<br><br>Now, these scenerios are all assuming that we are fighting one monster at a time. It gets a little tricky when fighting a mob. I only use DD attacks. I have not used AoE's since about level 8. I have just never had any use for them. They dont do as much damage to each creature as a DD, and it almost always results in pulling a mob onto myself. I have found that I can be most effective to use my most powerful spells and hit one at a time (only the ones that our tanks are fighting, and after losing 15- 20% of its health) to kill the monsters quickly, using all my mana if need be. I also may root 1 or 2 so the tanks can concentrate on one at a time. If I am sow'd and we have got way too many on us, I have been known to nuke a couple of them to draw them on to me, then run them around until our tanks have finished killing the others, then bring the monsters back or just run them to zone.<br><br>Someone posted on here saying not&nbsp;&nbsp;to fight melee. I have even heard some people say not to carry a weapon at all past a certain level. I disagree with that wholeheartedly. Now I'm not suggesting that you try to fight melee all the time like a warrior, expecting to do a lot of damage. But like it or not, melee fighting is the only way to build up your defense skills, like dodge. What I do is this....I said before that usually fighting a blue or green, I sit and med through it. Well, If I am full mana, I will get in and swing the staff around. I am certainly not expecting to do a lot of damage to the thing I am fighting. I do it mainly to pass the time (since my mana is full). But it also doesnt hurt to have your offense skills go up either. Right now my 2H Blunt skill is average. My offense is good, and my defense is very good (I am currently level 24 and carry a fine steel staff) and I fight melee better than most other casters I've ever been grouped with.<br><br> And even though these skills still may not be very important to a group, they have been extremely valuable in soloing. I cant tell you how many times I have had very close calls in a fight because I ran out of mana and had to finish the fight off with my staff. Then going back and looking at all the dodges I had done, or the misses from the monster. Also, when fighting those pesky greens that attack me even though I get no exp, I almost always fight melee through the majority of it when I can. That keeps me from wasting precious mana.<br><br>The wizard's battle skills lies in magic casting. And that should be the way you fight for the most part. But I think it's important to have some half-way decent melee skills and a good weapon for those times when you are out of mana or just want to conserve.<br><br>This is just my opinion, but it has worked for me very well. I suppose if you asked 10 different wizards what the best way to play the character is, you'd get 10 different answers.The good thing about Everquest is there is no one way you have to play your character, I dont care what it is. Just experiment and find out what works best for you. If your group doesnt like the way you are playing, drop out and find another group until you do. Now, I guess if you are constantly getting kicked out of groups because of the way you play, you might want to consider a new strategy. But the important thing is to have fun, and have fun playing it your way.<br><br>Vanderboz<br>24'th level wizzy<br>The Rathe<br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
